        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>* Spectral Setup

From the PdBI observations (see Figure 2 of proposal for HC3N) and from
the expected altitude for the HC3N and CH3CN emissions, we can expect
the linewidth not to be larger than 10 MHz but with a very fine
structure in the center of the line. The spectral resolution needed to
obtain the line shape should be better than 50 kHz. Within band 9, we
select 4 spectral windows centered at 645.1 GHz for HC3N(71-70), 663.3
GHz for HC3N(73-72), 643.1 GHz for CH3CN(35-34), and 661.5 GHz for
CH3CN(36-35). The spectral setup is chosen with a bandwidth of 58 MHz
and a spectral resolution of 30 kHz, with the final spectra smoothed
offline down to 50 kHz. The multiplet structures of these transitions
which can appear in LSB and USB will be used to discriminate them for
the DSB in Band 9.

* Sensitivity, imaging, calibration

The strength of the lines are estimated to be around 2 and 10 Jy for the
HC3N and CH3CN transitions, respectively. We request to have at least a
S/N~10 for the weakest lines and thus we plan to reach an rms of about
160 mJy with 50 kHz of spectral resolution. This requires about 20
minutes on source at band 9 with calculator-chosen weather conditions.

Imaging will be straightforward. The disk of Titan will be fully covered
by the primary beam, the largest angular scale of the most extended
configuration available at band 9 will be much larger than the diameter
of the disk (from 0.6 to 0.8 arcsec throughout Cycle 2), and the dynamic
range will be maximum ~60, which is easily reachable using standard
calibration (bandpass cal, and phase cal at less than 15deg).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
