    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Over the past three decades, the atmosphere of Titan has been studied by
many ground and space observatories, such that we are now starting to
understand its complexities. In the mm/sub-mm, it has been observed with
the IRAM 30m telescope, the PdB Interferometer and the JCMT. One of the
major results was the determination of the stratospheric vertical
profiles of HCN, HC3N, and CH3CN. In particular, HC3N and CH3CN have
been mapped using the PdBI at 230 GHz with a beam of 0.7" (compared to
the 1" size of Titan). Data analysis indicated spatial variations
between  the northern and southern hemispheres, as also observed by
Cassini/CIRS. Temporal variations were also confirmed. What is
critically missing now is a detailed view of these latitudinal and
temporal variations. We are proposing here to observe HC3N and CH3CN on
Titan at band 9, every six months. The results will provide
unprecedented high-resolution spatial and vertical distributions of both
compounds and help understand the coupling between chemistry and
dynamical processes in this unique atmosphere.
</prp:abstract>
